**Version Used**: 
https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/commit/467f6acb07ad34105a9e5d3405ec8fdd1701fc86

**Steps to Reproduce**:
Given
```csharp
public record Foo( string Name, IEnumerable<int> Items) {}
```

The following code produces false and false.
```csharp
    var a = new Foo("a", new int[] { 1, 2 });
    var b = new Foo("a", new int[] { 1, 2 });
        
    Console.WriteLine(a.Equals(b));
    Console.WriteLine(a == b);
```

Whereas the following code produces true and true.

```csharp
    var coll = new int[] { 1, 2 };
    var a = new Foo("a", coll);
    var b = new Foo("a", coll);

    Console.WriteLine(a.Equals(b));
    Console.WriteLine(a == b);
```

The generated equality comparer for the record uses `EqualityComparer<IEnumerable<int>>.Default`  to compare the Items collection which is just checking for reference equality .

**Expected Behavior**:

The generated `IEquatable<Foo>.Equals` override should compare structurally to be consistent with other types of properties.

**Actual Behavior**:

Records with collection properties should compare the collection structurally.

